&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; There a test definition is a method call (instead of a method
&gt; &gt; definition in JUnit) that registers a test for execution. It looks
&gt; roughly
&gt; &gt; like this:
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; class MyTestClass{
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; test(&quot;The test name&quot;){
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; // the actual test goes here
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; }
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; }
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; With this approach things like Rules become extremly trivial, since
&gt; all
&gt; &gt; you have to do is wrap the code block (i.e. closure) in a new new code
&gt; &gt; block.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Also parameterized test become fairly easy, because you would just
&gt; put
&gt; &gt; the call to test in a loop.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; What do you think? Is this an interesting direction for JUnit to go?
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;
